## Step 1 — Handle dirty base worktree

Find the worktree where `{{BASE_BRANCH}}` is checked out. If not found, use `{{WORKTREE_PATH}}` and check out `{{BASE_BRANCH}}` there.

Print `  Checking base worktree…`
Run: `git status --porcelain` in the base worktree.

- If clean: print `  ✓ Base worktree clean`
- If dirty: print `  ⚠ Base worktree has uncommitted changes — stashing…`
  Run: `git stash push -u -m "tachikoma auto-stash before ship ({{SLUG}})"`
  Print `  ✓ Stashed  (will restore after merge)`
  Set a flag to pop the stash after Step 3.

After Step 3 (squash-merge), if stash was created:
  Print `  Restoring stash…`
  Run: `git stash pop`
  - On success: print `  ✓ Stash restored`
  - On conflict: print:
    ```
      ⚠ Stash pop conflict — your stashed changes conflict with the merge.
        Resolve manually:
          cd <base-worktree>
          git status        # see conflicting files
          git add <files> && git stash drop
    ```
    Proceed — the merge already landed, this doesn't block cleanup or the PR.

## Step 2 — Log the diff

Print `  Diffing changes…`
Run:
```
git log {{TACHIKOMA_BRANCH}} ^{{BASE_BRANCH}} --oneline
git diff {{BASE_BRANCH}}...{{TACHIKOMA_BRANCH}} --stat
```
Print output verbatim (indented 2 spaces), then print `  ✓ <N> commits, <M> files changed`

## Step 3 — Squash-merge

Print `  Squash-merging into {{BASE_BRANCH}}…`
Run:
```
git checkout {{BASE_BRANCH}}   # in base worktree, only if not already there
git merge --squash {{TACHIKOMA_BRANCH}}
git commit -m "{{COMMIT_MESSAGE}}"
```
- On success: print `  ✓ Squash-merged  (<commit-sha>)` — capture the SHA.
- On conflict: run `git merge --abort`, then print:
  ```
    ✗ Merge conflict — cannot auto-merge {{TACHIKOMA_BRANCH}} into {{BASE_BRANCH}}
      Conflicting files:
        <list files>
      Work is on branch {{TACHIKOMA_BRANCH}} — run /tachikoma done to resolve manually.
  ```
  Then exit with code 1.

## Step 4 — Worktree + branch cleanup

Print `  Cleaning up worktree…`
Run:
```
git worktree remove {{WORKTREE_PATH}}
# if that fails due to untracked files:
git worktree remove --force {{WORKTREE_PATH}}
git branch -D {{TACHIKOMA_BRANCH}}
```
Print `  ✓ Worktree + branch removed`

## Step 5 — Push + open PR

Print `  Pushing {{BASE_BRANCH}}…`
Check for a remote: `git remote -v`. If none, print `  ⚠ No remote — skipping PR` and jump to Step 6.

Run: `git push -u origin {{BASE_BRANCH}}`
Print `  ✓ Pushed`

Print `  Opening PR…`
Run:
```
gh pr create \
  --title "{{PR_TITLE}}" \
  --body-file .tachikoma/ship_body.txt \
  --base {{PR_TARGET_BRANCH}} \
  --head {{BASE_BRANCH}}
```
Capture the printed PR URL. Print `  ✓ PR opened  <PR_URL>`

Then link the PR to the queued work-request so PROXY's pr_sync poller can auto-flip `status` to `done` on merge/close:

Print `  Linking PR to work_request…`
Run: `proxy queue link {{SLUG}} <PR_URL>`

- On success: print `  ✓ PR linked  (auto-done on merge)`.
- On non-zero exit (no matching slug in the DB, daemon unreachable, `proxy` CLI absent on PATH, etc.): print `  ⚠ proxy queue link failed — github_pr not set (work-queue row will need /work-queue done {{SLUG}})` and continue. This is best-effort: the PR is already open, and Step 7 (work-queue cleanup) is the legacy backstop for rows the daemon doesn't know about.

